content.description: This thin crack in a dihedral is a short route but surprisingly difficult for the grade. The crux is just before pulling the top rounded ledge.
content.protection: Small to medium gear. Many options for setting up an anchor at the top
content.location: This is to the right of Used Cars, even more right of Nuevos Huevos. It is in a left facing dihedral, not to be confused with Used Cars which is right facing.

climbs.name: Used Cars
climbs.fa: Unknown (Graham Ganssle up/down climbed it clean in Jan 2021)

content.description: Short, good route that tapers up wide at top. Easy as a lay-back but much more challenging using your off-width skills. Not sure why this route wasn't submitted before, as it's referenced in the Viejos Huevos route entry. If I submitted it incorrectly, please let me know I'll be happy to change or delete it. Thanks.
content.location: Facing the wall, this is just left of Viejos Huevos (and right of Nuevos Huevos). It is the wide crack in a right facing dihedral, not to be confused with Viejos Huevos which is the thin crack in the left facing dihedral.

content.description:
Unique, super fun granite hueco problem. Rock is more solid than it looks. Sit start.  

  I couldn't find it in any guidebook, so if anyone knows a different name for this problem, or climbed it before me, let me know and I'll update the info!
content.location: On the northwest side of Freshman Mountain, on top of the slab. Fairly visible and out in the open.

climbs.name: Return to the Planet of the Proks

content.description: Slightly overhanging dihedral. Layback and scum your way up. Great foot nubs all the way up. Bush underneath makes it undesirable...but the problem is really cool.Its the dihedral in image above...not where the climber is bouldering.
content.location: About 200 ft right of Viejos Huevos. If on trail on Freshman Dome from the west...traverse across the middle of dome and boulders will be on your left. Obvious boulders with bush at base of the dihedral.

content.description: Thin finger crack in a dihedral.
content.location: to the right of "me and my little fingers "

content.description: Left end of Yellow Pages. Wide crack.
Face problem on left side of arête. Beautiful, solid rock...trust crystals and feet.
content.location: About 200 ft right of Viejos Huevos. If on trail on Freshman Dome from the west...traverse across the middle of dome and boulders will be on your left. Obvious boulders with bush at base of the dihedral. Right of dihedral.

content.description: long diagonal crack that turns straight up towards the end. crack narrows as you go with a large opening about half way up.
content.protection: small to medium. fairly hard to make an anchor at the tom, consider using off-set cams.
content.location: covered in trees left of yellow pages.

content.description: Delicate stems lead to an excellent hand crack.
content.protection: Traditionally a boulder problem, it can also be lead on medium gear or top roped. Take medium to larger size gear for a TR anchor.
content.location: Located near the top of the wall formed by huge boulders on the Southwest side of Freshman's.

content.description: Flaring finger crack with a cool kneebar start. Work your way up the blocks at the base to put in your first .2, then it's insecure finger locks to the top. We used a .2, a .5, and a .4. There's an optional .3 at the very top if you want a piece as you pull over the (not as easy as you'll hope) top out. We built the anchor out of a .5, a .75, and a brown tricam. To put in some beta burns on top rope, we used a .1 in a little flake to climbers right for a directional.
content.protection: Climb: .2, .5, .4, .3. Anchor: 5., .75, brown tricam (probably a 1 would work), and a .1 for a TR redirect.
content.location: Just uphill of Yellow Pages proper. Head into the boulder field up the hill and back one set of boulders. You'll see the crack from the hillside.

content.description: This overhanging diheadral hand to offwidth crack can be bouldered relatively safely, but can be a fun lead. The crux is when the crack changes from hands to offwidth.
content.protection: #2-#5 C4, no anchors. The #5 is to protect the hand traverse on top of the boulder (definitely needed for protection of the 2nd to keep them from swinging into a jagged flake if they fall).
content.location: West face of Freshman Mountain, 100 yards uphill from Rock Clark Wall. Look for a short overhanging dihedral. Downclimb the slab to the climbers right for the descent. Be careful as some of the rock is rotten.

content.description: Climb the hand to offwidth crack in the right side of an almost squeeze chimney. It gets really interesting up towards the top! I can't find this climb in any guidebooks, so if anyone knows of a prior ascent, let me know so I can update this.
content.protection: Hand to fist cams. No anchors.
content.location: Just to the right of "Hang On Motherfucker", under the huge flake. It is about 100 yards uphill from the Rock Clark wall. Downclimb the slab to the climbers right for the descent. Be careful as some of the rock is rotten.

climbs.name: Chalupa Taco Combo
climbs.fa: James Crump, Robert Price, Steve Lowry (per the Dome Driver Manual)

content.description: This easy but fun problem exploits uniquely featured holds.
content.location: Found below The Good Book and Dirty Deeds on the Southwest side of Freshman's.
